<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 📘 Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 What are Swing Controls?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Formal KTU Definition:**
> *Swing Controls are the lightweight, platform-independent GUI (Graphical User Interface) components provided by `javax.swing` package in Java. They extend the `JComponent` class (which itself extends `java.awt.Container` → `java.awt.Component`) and follow the **Model-View-Controller (MVC)** architecture, where the **Model** holds the data, the **View** renders the visual representation, and the **Controller** handles user interaction via event listeners.*

### 🧠 Intuitive Analogy — The "Smart Remote Control" Analogy

Imagine you are designing the dashboard of a modern car:

- **Every knob, button, slider, and digital display** on the dashboard is a **Swing Control**.
- The **steering wheel buttons** (JButton) trigger an action (like honking).
- The **fuel gauge** (JProgressBar) reflects a *model* value (fuel level in liters).
- The **gear indicator** (JComboBox) lets the user select **one of N fixed options**.
- The **music volume slider** (JSlider) lets the user *smoothly drag* between a min and max value.
- The **checkboxes for AC/Heater** (JCheckBox) allow **independent on/off** choices.

In Java terms, **Swing Controls = interactive dashboard widgets** of your application window (`JFrame`).

### 1.2 The Swing Class Hierarchy (Foundational Map)

```
java.lang.Object
   └── java.awt.Component
         └── java.awt.Container
               └── javax.swing.JComponent   ← Base class for ALL Swing controls
                     ├── JLabel
                     ├── JButton
                     ├── JTextField
                     ├── JTextArea
                     ├── JCheckBox
                     ├── JRadioButton
                     ├── JComboBox
                     ├── JList
                     ├── JSlider
                     ├── JProgressBar
                     ├── JScrollPane
                     ├── JMenuBar → JMenu → JMenuItem
                     ├── JTable
                     ├── JTree
                     └── JTabbedPane
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Lightweight vs Heavyweight:** All Swing components are **lightweight** (100% Java-rendered, not relying on the host OS's native peers), unlike their AWT predecessors. This is why Swing GUIs look identical across Windows, macOS, and Linux — the **Java Look and Feel (PLAF)** controls rendering.

### 1.3 Why Swing Controls? (The "Why" Behind the Concept)

| Limitation in AWT | Solution Offered by Swing |
|---|---|
| Heavyweight (OS-dependent) | **Lightweight** (pure Java, PLAF-driven) |
| Limited component set | **Rich, pluggable** component library |
| No MVC separation | **Strict MVC** decoupling |
| "Dead" components (no pluggable look) | **Pluggable Look and Feel (PLAF)** support |

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 📘 Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 Universal Constructor & Setup Pattern

Every Swing control follows the **same 3-step usage pattern**:

1. **Declaration** → declare a reference of the control's class.
2. **Instantiation** → call the constructor (often passing a label/text/icon).
3. **Configuration** → call setter methods (`setBounds`, `setFont`, `setBackground`, etc.).
4. **Registration** → add an event listener (for interactive controls).
5. **Attachment** → `add()` the control to a container (e.g., `JFrame`).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Tip:** Marks are frequently awarded for the *correct sequence* — Declaration → Instantiation → Configuration → Listener → Add to Container. Writing the steps out of order in an exam is a common mark-loser.

## 2.2 The Master Reference Table — All Major Swing Controls

> [!NOTE]
> The table below is the **single most important cheat sheet** for KTU exams on this topic. Memorize the constructor signatures and key methods.

| Control | Class | Key Constructor(s) | Key Methods | Event / Listener |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Label** | `JLabel` | `JLabel()`, `JLabel(String)`, `JLabel(Icon)`, `JLabel(String, int align)` | `setText()`, `getText()`, `setIcon()`, `setHorizontalAlignment()` | None (passive) |
| **Button** | `JButton` | `JButton()`, `JButton(String)`, `JButton(Icon)` | `setEnabled()`, `setIcon()`, `doClick()` | `ActionListener` → `actionPerformed()` |
| **Text Field** | `JTextField` | `JTextField(int cols)`, `JTextField(String)`, `JTextField(String, int cols)` | `getText()`, `setText()`, `setEditable(false)`, `setEchoChar()` | `ActionListener` |
| **Password Field** | `JPasswordField` | `JPasswordField(int cols)` | `getPassword()` *(returns `char[]`)* | `ActionListener` |
| **Text Area** | `JTextArea` | `JTextArea(int rows, int cols)`, `JTextArea(String)` | `append()`, `setLineWrap()`, `setText()` | (Usually wrapped in `JScrollPane`) |
| **Scroll Pane** | `JScrollPane` | `JScrollPane(Component view)` | `setVerticalScrollBarPolicy()` | None |
| **Check Box** | `JCheckBox` | `JCheckBox(String)`, `JCheckBox(String, boolean selected)` | `isSelected()`, `setSelected(boolean)` | `ItemListener` → `itemStateChanged()` |
| **Radio Button** | `JRadioButton` | `JRadioButton(String)`, `JRadioButton(String, boolean)` | `isSelected()`, `setSelected(boolean)` | `ItemListener` |
| **Button Group** | `ButtonGroup` | `ButtonGroup()` | `add(AbstractButton)` | None — enforces **mutual exclusion** |
| **Combo Box** | `JComboBox` | `JComboBox()`, `JComboBox(Object[] items)` | `getSelectedItem()`, `getSelectedIndex()`, `addItem()` | `ActionListener` / `ItemListener` |
| **List** | `JList` | `JList()`, `JList(Object[] items)`, `JList(ListModel)` | `getSelectedValue()`, `getSelectedValuesList()`, `setSelectionMode()` | `ListSelectionListener` |
| **Slider** | `JSlider` | `JSlider(int min, int max, int value)`, `JSlider(int orientation)` | `getValue()`, `setValue()`, `setMajorTickSpacing()`, `setPaintTicks()` | `ChangeListener` → `stateChanged()` |
| **Progress Bar** | `JProgressBar` | `JProgressBar(int min, int max)`, `JProgressBar(int orientation)` | `setValue()`, `getValue()`, `setStringPainted(true)` | None (data-driven) |
| **Menu Bar** | `JMenuBar` | `JMenuBar()` | `add(JMenu)` | None |
| **Menu** | `JMenu` | `JMenu(String)` | `add(JMenuItem)`, `addSeparator()` | None |
| **Menu Item** | `JMenuItem` | `JMenuItem(String)`, `JMenuItem(Icon)` | `setAccelerator(KeyStroke)`, `setMnemonic(char)` | `ActionListener` |
| **Table** | `JTable` | `JTable(Object[][] data, Object[] cols)`, `JTable(TableModel)` | `getValueAt()`, `setValueAt()`, `getSelectedRow()` | `ListSelectionListener` |
| **Tree** | `JTree` | `JTree(Object[])`, `JTree(TreeModel)` | `getSelectionPath()`, `expandPath()` | `TreeSelectionListener` |
| **Tabbed Pane** | `JTabbedPane` | `JTabbedPane()`, `JTabbedPane(int tabPlacement)` | `addTab(String, Component)`, `getSelectedIndex()` | `ChangeListener` |
| **Option Pane** | `JOptionPane` | (Static methods used) | `showMessageDialog()`, `showInputDialog()`, `showConfirmDialog()` | None (returns value) |

## 2.3 The MVC Triad in Swing (Conceptual Deep-Dive)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Concept:** Each Swing control has an associated **Model** interface (e.g., `ButtonModel`, `ListModel`, `DocumentModel`). The default model is used unless explicitly replaced.

$$
\text{Swing Control} \;=\; \underbrace{\text{Model}}_{\text{data state}} \;+\; \underbrace{\text{View}}_{\text{delegate (UIResource)}} \;+\; \underbrace{\text{Controller (UI)}}_{\text{Event Listener + input map}}
$$

**Why is this important?**
- You can swap the **Look and Feel** (Windows / Metal / Nimbus / Motif) without changing the data model.
- You can replace the model with a custom subclass — for example, replacing `DefaultListModel` with a custom model that loads items from a database.

## 2.4 Event Handling Recap (The "Glue" of Swing)

| Listener Interface | Method | Typical Use |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent)` | Button click, Enter in text field, menu selection |
| `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent)` | Checkbox toggle, radio button select, combo box change |
| `ChangeListener` | `stateChanged(ChangeEvent)` | Slider drag, progress bar update, tab switch |
| `ListSelectionListener` | `valueChanged(ListSelectionEvent)` | Row selection in `JList` or `JTable` |
| `KeyListener` | `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased` | Keyboard input on any component |
| `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked`, `mouseEntered`, ... | Mouse events |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Exam Watch:** Always register listeners with `component.addXxxListener(new XxxListener() { ... })` **before** adding the component to its container. The reverse order compiles fine but is considered "bad form" by examiners.

## 2.5 Layout Managers — The "Skeleton" That Holds Controls

Controls placed on a container need a **Layout Manager** to position them. The 5 essential KTU layout managers:

| Layout | Behavior | Constructor |
|---|---|---|
| `FlowLayout` | Left-to-right, wraps to next line | `new FlowLayout(int align, int hgap, int vgap)` |
| `BorderLayout` | 5 regions: NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, WEST, CENTER | `new BorderLayout(int hgap, int vgap)` |
| `GridLayout` | Equal-sized grid | `new GridLayout(int rows, int cols, int hgap, int vgap)` |
| `GridBagLayout` | Flexible, constraint-based grid | `new GridBagLayout()` + `GridBagConstraints` |
| `BoxLayout` | Stacks components in a single axis | `new BoxLayout(container, int axis)` |

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 📘 Section 3: Step-by-Step Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Patterns

> [!NOTE]
> The following worked examples use the **canonical 5-step Swing pattern** and correspond to typical KTU Part B (14-mark) programming questions.

## 3.1 Worked Example A — Login Form with `JLabel`, `JTextField`, `JPasswordField`, `JButton`

**Question:** *Design a Swing login window with two text fields (username, password), two labels, a "Login" button, and a status label. On clicking Login, verify credentials "admin"/"java" and show success/failure.*

### Step 1 — Import statements

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

### Step 2 — Class declaration extending `JFrame`

```java
public class LoginDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
```

> The class implements `ActionListener` so the frame itself can handle button events — this avoids creating a separate listener class.

### Step 3 — Declare components as instance fields

```java
    JLabel lblUser, lblPass, lblStatus;
    JTextField txtUser;
    JPasswordField txtPass;
    JButton btnLogin;
```

### Step 4 — Constructor: configure frame + create & add components

```java
    LoginDemo() {
        setTitle("Login Window");
        setSize(350, 220);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER, 10, 10));
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        lblUser  = new JLabel("Username:");
        lblPass  = new JLabel("Password:");
        lblStatus = new JLabel(" ");

        txtUser  = new JTextField(15);
        txtPass  = new JPasswordField(15);
        btnLogin = new JButton("Login");

        btnLogin.addActionListener(this);   // Register listener FIRST

        add(lblUser);  add(txtUser);
        add(lblPass);  add(txtPass);
        add(btnLogin);
        add(lblStatus);

        setVisible(true);
    }
```

### Step 5 — Implement the `actionPerformed` callback

```java
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String u = txtUser.getText();
        String p = new String(txtPass.getPassword());   // char[] → String

        if (u.equals("admin") && p.equals("java")) {
            lblStatus.setText("✔ Login Successful");
            lblStatus.setForeground(Color.GREEN);
        } else {
            lblStatus.setText("✘ Invalid credentials");
            lblStatus.setForeground(Color.RED);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new LoginDemo();
    }
}
```

### Why this works — concept mapping

| Step | What happens internally |
|---|---|
| `setLayout(new FlowLayout(...))` | The frame's content pane uses a `FlowLayout` manager to position children in a row. |
| `btnLogin.addActionListener(this)` | The button stores a reference to the `LoginDemo` instance. When clicked, it fires an `ActionEvent` and calls `actionPerformed`. |
| `txtPass.getPassword()` | Returns a `char[]` (not `String`) for **security** — `String` is immutable and lingers in the String pool. |
| `setVisible(true)` | The frame is painted by the **Swing EDT (Event Dispatch Thread)**. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Some students write `txtPass.getText()`. This works in older compilers but is **deprecated since Java 5** and produces a compiler warning. Always use `getPassword()` and convert to `String` if needed.

---

## 3.2 Worked Example B — `JRadioButton` + `ButtonGroup` + `JComboBox` Pizza Order

**Question:** *Build a form where the user selects pizza size (radio buttons: Small/Medium/Large), toppings (checkboxes: Cheese/Mushroom/Olive), and crust type (combo box: Thin/Thick/Stuffed). On clicking "Show Order", display a summary in a `JTextArea`.*

### Step 1 — Imports

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

### Step 2 — Class & fields

```java
public class PizzaOrder extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JRadioButton rbSmall, rbMed, rbLarge;
    JCheckBox  cbCheese, cbMush, cbOlive;
    JComboBox<String> cbCrust;
    JButton btnShow;
    JTextArea taSummary;
    ButtonGroup bgSize;
```

### Step 3 — Build the GUI

```java
    PizzaOrder() {
        setTitle("Pizza Order");
        setSize(420, 320);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.LEFT));
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        // --- Size radio group ---
        JPanel pSize = new JPanel(new GridLayout(3,1));
        pSize.setBorder(BorderFactory.createTitledBorder("Size"));
        rbSmall = new JRadioButton("Small  ₹100", true);   // default selected
        rbMed   = new JRadioButton("Medium ₹200");
        rbLarge = new JRadioButton("Large  ₹300");
        bgSize = new ButtonGroup();           // enforces mutual exclusion
        bgSize.add(rbSmall); bgSize.add(rbMed); bgSize.add(rbLarge);
        pSize.add(rbSmall); pSize.add(rbMed); pSize.add(rbLarge);

        // --- Topping checkboxes ---
        JPanel pTop = new JPanel(new GridLayout(3,1));
        pTop.setBorder(BorderFactory.createTitledBorder("Toppings"));
        cbCheese = new JCheckBox("Cheese  +₹30");
        cbMush   = new JCheckBox("Mushroom +₹40");
        cbOlive  = new JCheckBox("Olive   +₹25");
        pTop.add(cbCheese); pTop.add(cbMush); pTop.add(cbOlive);

        // --- Crust combo ---
        JPanel pCrust = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());
        pCrust.setBorder(BorderFactory.createTitledBorder("Crust"));
        String[] crusts = {"Thin", "Thick", "Stuffed"};
        cbCrust = new JComboBox<>(crusts);
        pCrust.add(new JLabel("Type:")); pCrust.add(cbCrust);

        btnShow = new JButton("Show Order");
        btnShow.addActionListener(this);

        taSummary = new JTextArea(6, 30);
        taSummary.setEditable(false);
        JScrollPane sp = new JScrollPane(taSummary);

        add(pSize); add(pTop); add(pCrust);
        add(btnShow); add(sp);
        setVisible(true);
    }
```

### Step 4 — Compute the order on button click

```java
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        int total = 0;
        String size;

        if      (rbSmall.isSelected()) { size = "Small";  total += 100; }
        else if (rbMed.isSelected())   { size = "Medium"; total += 200; }
        else                           { size = "Large";  total += 300; }

        StringBuilder tops = new StringBuilder();
        if (cbCheese.isSelected()) { tops.append("Cheese, "); total += 30; }
        if (cbMush.isSelected())   { tops.append("Mushroom, "); total += 40; }
        if (cbOlive.isSelected())  { tops.append("Olive, "); total += 25; }

        String crust = (String) cbCrust.getSelectedItem();

        taSummary.setText("Size   : " + size +
                          "\nCrust  : " + crust +
                          "\nTopping: " + (tops.length()==0 ? "None" : tops.toString()) +
                          "\nTotal  : ₹" + total);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new PizzaOrder(); }
}
```

### Concept Mapping

| Construct | Purpose | Listener |
|---|---|---|
| `JRadioButton` + `ButtonGroup` | **Mutually exclusive** choice | `ItemListener` (we polled with `isSelected()` instead) |
| `JCheckBox` | **Independent** boolean choices | `ItemListener` |
| `JComboBox` | Pick **one** from a fixed list | `ActionListener` |
| `JTextArea` + `JScrollPane` | Multi-line **read-only output** | None |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Trick Question:** *"What happens if you don't use a `ButtonGroup` with multiple `JRadioButton`?"* — **Answer:** Each radio button behaves as an **independent toggle** (you can select ALL of them simultaneously), defeating the purpose of "radio" semantics. The `ButtonGroup` is what enforces the **at-most-one** invariant.

---

## 3.3 Worked Example C — `JSlider` + `JProgressBar` Temperature Monitor

**Question:** *Create a window with a horizontal `JSlider` (range 0–100) and a `JProgressBar` that mirrors the slider's value in real time. Display the numeric value in a label.*

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import javax.swing.event.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class TempMonitor extends JFrame {
    JSlider slider;
    JProgressBar bar;
    JLabel lbl;

    TempMonitor() {
        setTitle("Temperature Monitor");
        setSize(400, 180);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        slider = new JSlider(JSlider.HORIZONTAL, 0, 100, 25);
        slider.setMajorTickSpacing(20);
        slider.setMinorTickSpacing(5);
        slider.setPaintTicks(true);
        slider.setPaintLabels(true);

        bar = new JProgressBar(0, 100);
        bar.setValue(25);
        bar.setStringPainted(true);

        lbl = new JLabel("Current: 25 °C");

        slider.addChangeListener(e -> {
            int v = slider.getValue();
            bar.setValue(v);
            lbl.setText("Current: " + v + " °C");
        });

        add(new JLabel("Temperature:"));
        add(slider);
        add(lbl);
        add(bar);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new TempMonitor(); }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Java 8+ Feature Used:** Lambda expression `e -> { ... }` is shorthand for `new ChangeListener() { public void stateChanged(ChangeEvent e) { ... } }`. KTU exams accept either notation; lambda is more concise.

