# 📘 Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

## 📝 PART A — 3-Mark Short Answer Questions

### Q1. `[KTU University Exam — June 2024]`
**Differentiate between `JTextField` and `JTextArea` in Java Swing. Mention at least two differences.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | `JTextField` | `JTextArea` |
|---|---|---|
| **Lines of text** | Single-line only | Multi-line (rows × cols) |
| **Typical use** | Short input (name, age, password) | Paragraphs, logs, summaries |
| **Scrolling** | Not scrollable | Usually wrapped in `JScrollPane` |
| **Constructor example** | `new JTextField(15)` | `new JTextArea(5, 20)` |
| **Word wrap** | Not applicable | `setLineWrap(true)` available |

*(Examiner awards 1 mark for each valid difference; minimum 2 expected.)*

---

### Q2. `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`
**What is the role of `ButtonGroup` in Swing? Why can't we achieve the same effect using a regular `JPanel`?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

- `ButtonGroup` is a logical container that enforces **mutual exclusion** among its member `AbstractButton`s (typically `JRadioButton`s) — **at most one can be selected at a time**. *(1 mark)*
- When a new button is selected, the previously selected one is automatically deselected by the group's `ButtonModel`. *(1 mark)*
- A `JPanel` is only a **physical/visual** container; it does not coordinate the selected state of its child buttons. Multiple radio buttons inside a `JPanel` can be selected **simultaneously** because their `ButtonModel`s are independent. Only `ButtonGroup` wires the models together. *(1 mark)*

---

## 📝 PART B — 14-Mark Long Answer (Module Internal Choice)

> **Note:** Two independent choices are given. Students answer **either** Question A **or** Question B.

---

### ❓ Question A (14 Marks) — `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2024 Model Paper]`

**(a) [7 Marks]** Explain the **MVC architecture** as applied to Java Swing controls. State the role of the Model, View, and Controller with one example each.

**(b) [7 Marks]** Write a complete Java Swing program to create a **simple calculator** that performs addition and subtraction of two numbers entered via `JTextField`s. Use a `JButton` labeled `"="` to compute and display the result in a non-editable `JTextField`. Use `BorderLayout` for the frame.

---

#### ✅ Model Solution — Part (a) [7 Marks]

**MVC Architecture in Swing:**

Swing was the first Java GUI toolkit built around a **strict Model-View-Controller separation**. This means that for every control, three orthogonal pieces exist:

$$
\boxed{\text{Swing Control} = \text{Model} + \text{View} + \text{Controller}}
$$

**1. Model (Data State)** — *(2 marks)*
- Holds the *internal state* of the control. It is **data-only**, with no rendering logic.
- Examples:
  - `ButtonModel` → stores `isArmed()`, `isPressed()`, `isSelected()` flags for a `JButton` / `JRadioButton` / `JCheckBox`.
  - `BoundedRangeModel` → stores `(value, minimum, maximum, extent)` for a `JSlider` or `JProgressBar`.
  - `ListModel` / `TableModel` / `TreeModel` → store the rows of a `JList` / `JTable` / `JTree`.
- You can swap the default model with a custom subclass without touching the view.

**2. View (Rendering / Delegate)** — *(2 marks)*
- Renders the model onto the screen. Swing does not draw the pixels itself — it delegates to a **UIResource** object (e.g., `ButtonUI`, `SliderUI`, `BasicScrollBarUI`).
- The view is bound to the **Pluggable Look and Feel (PLAF)** — switching `UIManager.setLookAndFeel(...)` replaces the view while the model remains untouched.
- This is the **secret** behind Swing's "write once, render anywhere" promise.

**3. Controller (Event Handling)** — *(2 marks)*
- Handles user input (mouse, keyboard, focus).
- In Swing, the controller is split into:
  - The **UI** delegate (low-level: mouse-over highlighting, focus rings).
  - The **user-registered Listener** (high-level: `ActionListener`, `ChangeListener`, etc., which you write).
- Listeners mutate the **model**; the model fires a `ChangeEvent`; the view repaints. This is the **observer pattern** in action.

**Concrete example: `JSlider`**
- *Model:* `BoundedRangeModel` holds `value=42, min=0, max=100`.
- *View:* `SliderUI` paints the track, knob, and tick marks.
- *Controller:* A `ChangeListener` registered on the slider is invoked on drag → you call `model.setValue(50)`, which fires a `ChangeEvent` → the view repaints.

**Advantages of MVC in Swing (1 mark):**
- Swappable look & feel without touching data.
- Reusable models (one `ListModel` can back a `JList` and a `JTable` column).
- Testable UI logic (model can be unit-tested headlessly).

