## 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs & Code Derivations

> **[!NOTE]**
> For an Object-Oriented Programming course, "derivations" are equivalent to **writing complete programs step-by-step**. Below are exhaustive, line-by-line constructions of the most frequently asked Swing programs in KTU examinations.

### 3.1 Derivation 1 — The "Hello Swing" Skeleton (Base Program)

**Problem:** Create a Swing application that displays a `JFrame` titled "My First Swing App" with a `JLabel` saying "Hello, World!" in the center, sized 400×300, and exits on close.

#### Step-by-Step Construction:

**Step 1:** Import the required packages. The `javax.swing.*` wildcard imports all swing classes; `java.awt.*` provides the `BorderLayout` and `Color`.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
```

**Step 2:** Ensure the GUI is created on the **Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)** for thread safety.

```java
public class HelloSwing {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> {
            createAndShowGUI();
        });
    }
}
```

**Step 3:** Create the `JFrame` (the top-level window), configure its title, default close operation, size, and visibility.

```java
    private static void createAndShowGUI() {
        // Create the window
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("My First Swing App");

        // Define what happens when user clicks the 'X' button
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        // Set window size (width=400, height=300)
        frame.setSize(400, 300);

        // Center the window on the screen
        frame.setLocationRelativeTo(null);
    }
```

**Step 4:** Add a `JLabel` (display component) to the **content pane** (where all components go inside a `JFrame`). Use `BorderLayout.CENTER` to place it in the middle.

```java
        // Create a label
        JLabel label = new JLabel("Hello, World!", SwingConstants.CENTER);

        // Add label to the frame's content pane (centered by default)
        frame.getContentPane().add(label, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // Make the window visible
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

> **[!TIP]**
> **Explanation of every line:**
> - `SwingConstants.CENTER` horizontally and vertically centers the text within the label itself.
> - `getContentPane().add(...)` is used because in Swing, you don't add components directly to a `JFrame`; you add them to its **content pane** (a `JPanel`).
> - `setVisible(true)` must be the **last** call, otherwise the window may appear blank for a split second.

