#### **Question B (14 Marks) — Choice 2**
**Q4. [KTU University Exam — Model Question based on December 2024 Pattern]**
**(a)** Explain **Pluggable Look and Feel (PLAF)** in Swing. Write the code to change the look-and-feel of a Swing application to the system look-and-feel. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Write a Java Swing program that uses a `JMenuBar` with **File** and **Edit** menus. The File menu should have Open, Save, and Exit items. The Edit menu should have Cut, Copy, and Paste items. Use appropriate `ActionListener`s to display messages using `JOptionPane` when menu items are clicked. *(7 marks)*

#### **Model Solution (a):**

**Pluggable Look and Feel (PLAF)** is a mechanism that allows a Swing application to dynamically change the appearance of its components *without* changing the application code. The look-and-feel is controlled by the `javax.swing.UIManager` class, which delegates the actual rendering of every component to a "UI Delegate" object.

**Types of PLAF in Java:**
1. **Metal** (default, cross-platform) — `javax.swing.plaf.metal.MetalLookAndFeel`
2. **System** (native OS look) — obtained via `UIManager.getSystemLookAndFeelClassName()`
3. **Nimbus** (modern Java look) — `javax.swing.plaf.nimbus.NimbusLookAndFeel`
4. **Motif, GTK, Windows, Mac** — OS-specific

**Code to Apply System Look-and-Feel:**

```java
import javax.swing.*;

public class PLAFDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Step 1: Get the system L&F class name
            String systemLF = UIManager.getSystemLookAndFeelClassName();

            // Step 2: Set the L&F
            UIManager.setLookAndFeel(systemLF);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Step 3: Launch the GUI normally
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> {
            JFrame frame = new JFrame("PLAF Demo");
            frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
            frame.setSize(300, 200);
            frame.add(new JLabel("Hello with System L&F", SwingConstants.CENTER));
            frame.setVisible(true);
        });
    }
}
```

> **[!IMPORTANT]**
> The L&F must be set **BEFORE** any Swing component is created; otherwise, existing components will not update their appearance. Use `SwingUtilities.updateComponentTreeUI(frame)` to update an already-visible frame.

#### **Model Solution (b):**

