# 🎯 SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Swing Buttons** are interactive **GUI components** derived from the abstract class `javax.swing.AbstractButton` that allow a user to initiate an action, toggle a state, or select one or more options in a Java desktop application. They are the fundamental control widgets of the **Java Foundation Classes (JFC)** and are housed in the `javax.swing` package.

In the KTU 2024 Scheme (NEP 2020 aligned), the four primary Swing button types studied under **Object Oriented Programming Concepts** are:

| # | Class | Purpose | Multi-Select? |
|---|-------|---------|---------------|
| 1 | `JButton` | Standard push button (one-shot action trigger) | N/A |
| 2 | `JToggleButton` | Two-state push button (pressed / released) | Yes (independent) |
| 3 | `JCheckBox` | Multi-selection toggle (✓ / ☐) | Yes (independent) |
| 4 | `JRadioButton` | Mutually-exclusive selection (within `ButtonGroup`) | No (one of group) |

All of these inherit a common API from **`AbstractButton`**, which is itself a subclass of `JComponent`.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English

> [!NOTE]
> **Think of a TV Remote Control:**
> - **`JButton`** = the *Power* button — press it, an action happens, and it springs back.
> - **`JToggleButton`** = the *Mute* button — press once to stay down (muted), press again to pop back up.
> - **`JCheckBox`** = the *Subtitle ON/OFF* + *Audio Description ON/OFF* switches — you can turn **multiple** features on at the same time.
> - **`JRadioButton`** = the *HDMI-1 / HDMI-2 / AV* input selector — only **one** source can be active at a time.

When you press any of these, the button "fires" a **signal** (called an **Event** in OOP terminology). A small piece of code called a **Listener** is waiting to catch that signal and respond. This is the famous **Delegation Event Model** of Java.

## 1.3 Common Superclass: `AbstractButton`

The KTU 2024 module emphasizes that *all* four button types share the same parent class. Understanding the common API prevents code duplication.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Standard Metrics / Class Constants (bolded for memory):**
> - **Package:** `javax.swing`
> - **Root Class:** `java.lang.Object` → `java.awt.Component` → `java.awt.Container` → `javax.swing.JComponent` → **`javax.swing.AbstractButton`** → Concrete buttons
> - **Standard Listeners:** `ActionListener`, `ItemListener`, `ChangeListener`
> - **Default Look-and-Feel:** **Pluggable Look-and-Feel (PLAF)** — buttons render via UI Delegates

