# 🧠 SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Breakdown — The "Why" and "How"

### Why a class hierarchy?
Java's designers used **inheritance** to share the *Icon*, *Text*, *Mnemonic*, *Action Command*, *Enabled/Disabled state*, and *Event registration* logic across all four button types. The OOP principle at work is **code reusability through generalization**.

### How does a button respond to a click?
1. JVM detects a **mouse-press / mouse-release** inside the button's bounding rectangle.
2. The button's **UI Delegate** (a `ButtonUI` subclass) translates this to an `ActionEvent`.
3. The event is **dispatched** to every listener registered via `addActionListener()`.
4. The listener's `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` method executes.

For state-changing buttons (`JCheckBox`, `JRadioButton`, `JToggleButton`), an additional **`ItemEvent`** is fired whenever the selected state flips, handled by an `ItemListener` implementing `itemStateChanged()`.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Constructor & Method Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The following table consolidates the constructors, key methods, and event constants. For KTU 2024 ESE valuation, memorizing these signatures is worth **3-5 marks** of "direct recall" per question paper.

### 2.2.1 Common `AbstractButton` API (Inherited by ALL Swing Buttons)

| Method | Return Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `setText(String s)` | `void` | Sets the label |
| `getText()` | `String` | Returns the label |
| `setIcon(Icon i)` | `void` | Sets the icon |
| `setMnemonic(char c)` | `void` | Sets keyboard shortcut (Alt + c) |
| `setToolTipText(String s)` | `void` | Hover hint |
| `setEnabled(boolean b)` | `void` | Enable \vert disable the button |
| `addActionListener(ActionListener l)` | `void` | Register click handler |
| `addItemListener(ItemListener l)` | `void` | Register state-change handler |
| `setActionCommand(String cmd)` | `void` | Logical name for the event |
| `isSelected()` | `boolean` | For toggle/checkbox/radio |

### 2.2.2 Constructor Reference Table

| Class | Constructor | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `JButton` | `JButton()` | Empty button |
| `JButton` | `JButton(String text)` | Button with label |
| `JButton` | `JButton(Icon icon)` | Button with image |
| `JButton` | `JButton(String text, Icon icon)` | Text + Image |
| `JToggleButton` | `JToggleButton(String text)` | Two-state push button |
| `JToggleButton` | `JToggleButton(String text, boolean selected)` | Pre-set state |
| `JCheckBox` | `JCheckBox(String text)` | Checkable box |
| `JCheckBox` | `JCheckBox(String text, boolean selected)` | Pre-set state |
| `JRadioButton` | `JRadioButton(String text)` | Radio button |
| `JRadioButton` | `JRadioButton(String text, boolean selected)` | Pre-set state |

### 2.2.3 Event Constants Reference

| Constant | Class | Trigger |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent.ACTION_PERFORMED` | `ActionEvent` | Button clicked \vert activated |
| `ItemEvent.SELECTED` | `ItemEvent` | State became checked |
| `ItemEvent.DESELECTED` | `ItemEvent` | State became unchecked |

### 2.2.4 The `ButtonGroup` Container

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`ButtonGroup`** is **NOT** a visual container. It is a logical grouping that enforces *mutual exclusion* among `JRadioButton` (and also `JToggleButton` and `JCheckBoxMenuItem`) instances. It must still be added to a visible `Container` (e.g., `JPanel`) for display.

$$
\boxed{\text{ButtonGroup} \rightarrow \text{Logical Mutual-Exclusion} \; \big\vert \; \text{JPanel} \rightarrow \text{Physical Layout}}
$$

## 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

Swing buttons are the bedrock of:
- **Enterprise desktop dashboards** (banking, ERP systems)
- **IDE plugins** (NetBeans, IntelliJ internals use Swing-derived APIs)
- **Scientific simulation front-ends** (MATLAB-style GUIs in Java)
- **Kiosk applications** (ticket vending, ATM interfaces)

The **Model–View–Controller (MVC)** pattern used in Swing is directly applicable to modern frameworks like **JavaFX**, **Android (XML views + Activity controllers)**, and **Spring Web (Thymeleaf views + Controller classes)**.

