#### Model Solution (b) — 7 marks

```java
JRadioButton male   = new JRadioButton("Male");
JRadioButton female = new JRadioButton("Female");
JRadioButton other  = new JRadioButton("Other");

ButtonGroup g = new ButtonGroup();   // logical group
g.add(male);
g.add(female);
g.add(other);

// Then add the radio buttons (NOT the group) to a JPanel
JPanel p = new JPanel();
p.add(male); p.add(female); p.add(other);
add(p);
```

**Explanation (to be written in exam):**
- When the user selects any one `JRadioButton`, the `ButtonGroup` iterates through its members and calls `setSelected(false)` on all others. Thus, **at most one** is selected at any time.
- `ButtonGroup` extends `Object` directly, **not** `Component` or `Container`. It has **no visual representation**; therefore it cannot be added to a `JFrame` (which expects a `Component`). The individual `JRadioButton` components are added to a `JPanel`, and the `JPanel` is added to the frame.

