> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why `addActionListener()` on a text field?** A `JTextField` fires an **`ActionEvent`** when the user presses the **Enter** key. This is THE key integration point between **JTextField** and **Event Handling** — and is a direct KTU 2024 syllabus requirement.

## 2.2 Event Handling Mechanism — The Delegation Event Model

### 2.2.1 Conceptual Phases

1. **Event Source Identification:** Identify the GUI component (button, text field, mouse) capable of producing events.
2. **Listener Registration:** Call `source.addXListener(listenerObj)`. Internally, Java maintains a `EventListener` list per source.
3. **Event Occurrence:** User interacts — the AWT/Swing event-dispatch thread invokes the component's `processEvent()`.
4. **Event Dispatch:** `processEvent()` is overridden in the component to forward to `processActionEvent()`, `processKeyEvent()`, etc.
5. **Listener Notification:** Each registered listener's callback method is invoked **synchronously on the Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)**.
6. **Event Handling:** The method body of the listener executes — e.g., `textField.getText()` is read, computation runs, UI updates.

### 2.2.2 Master Table — Listener Interfaces & Their Callbacks (CRITICAL for KTU)

| Listener Interface | Package | Callback Method(s) | When Triggered |
|--------------------|---------|--------------------|----------------|
| `ActionListener` | `java.awt.event` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` | **Button click, Enter in JTextField, menu select** |
| `KeyListener` | `java.awt.event` | `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased(KeyEvent e)` | Keyboard input |
| `MouseListener` | `java.awt.event` | `mouseClicked`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited(MouseEvent e)` | Mouse button + enter/exit |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `java.awt.event` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved(MouseEvent e)` | Mouse movement |
| `WindowListener` | `java.awt.event` | `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, `windowIconified`, `windowDeiconified`, `windowActivated`, `windowDeactivated(WindowEvent e)` | Window lifecycle |
| `FocusListener` | `java.awt.event` | `focusGained`, `focusLost(FocusEvent e)` | Component gains/loses focus |
| `ItemListener` | `java.awt.event` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e)` | Checkbox/radio toggle, list selection |
| `AdjustmentListener` | `java.awt.event` | `adjustmentValueChanged(AdjustmentEvent e)` | Scrollbar movement |
| `TextListener` | `javax.swing.event` | `textValueChanged(TextEvent e)` | Text changes (legacy AWT `TextComponent`) |

### 2.2.3 Master Table — Adapter Classes (For Listener Interfaces with ≥ 2 Methods)

> [!NOTE]
> **Why Adapter Classes?** Listener interfaces with multiple methods (e.g., `WindowListener` has 7) force you to implement *all* methods even if you only need 1. **Adapters provide empty default implementations** — you override only what you need.

| Listener | Adapter Class | Use Case |
|----------|---------------|----------|
| `KeyListener` | `KeyAdapter` | Detect Enter on a text field — only `keyPressed` needed |
| `MouseListener` | `MouseAdapter` | Detect click — only `mouseClicked` needed |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `MouseMotionAdapter` | Drag tracking — only `mouseDragged` needed |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowAdapter` | Handle window close — only `windowClosing` needed |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusAdapter` | Validate input on `focusLost` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Rule of Thumb:** If the listener interface name ends in `Listener` AND has **more than one abstract method**, an adapter class is available in `java.awt.event` (or `javax.swing.event`) with the word `Adapter` substituted for `Listener`. **Exception:** `ActionListener` has only 1 method — no adapter exists.

## 2.3 Why the Delegation Event Model? — Engineering Utility

- **Decoupling:** UI components (the view) and event handlers (the controller) are separate objects → adheres to **MVC** and **Single Responsibility Principle**.
- **Reusability:** One listener can be registered to **multiple sources** (one handler for many buttons).
- **Multiple Listeners:** One source can have **many listeners** (e.g., both `ActionListener` and `KeyListener` on the same `JTextField`).
- **Thread Safety:** All events are dispatched on the **Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)** — critical for Swing's single-threaded rendering rule.

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Utility:** Industrial HMIs (Human-Machine Interfaces) in SCADA systems, ATM UIs, airline check-in kiosks, and medical device touchscreens all use the **Delegation Event Model** (or its direct descendant, JavaFX's EventHandler API) under the hood.
