# SECTION 3: STEP-BY-STEP DERIVATIONS & ANALYTICAL MATRIX

## 3.1 Problem Scenario 1 — Basic JTextField with ActionListener (Login Echo)

> **Specification:** Create a Swing window containing a `JTextField` (10 columns), a `JButton` ("Greet"), and a `JLabel`. On clicking the button OR pressing Enter inside the text field, the label should display *"Hello, &lt;name&gt;!"* and the field should be cleared.

### Step 1 — Import packages

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

*Textual explanation:* `javax.swing.*` provides `JFrame`, `JTextField`, `JButton`, `JLabel`, `JPanel`. `java.awt.*` provides `FlowLayout` and `Dimension`. `java.awt.event.*` provides `ActionListener` and `ActionEvent`.

### Step 2 — Extend JFrame and declare components

```java
public class GreetApp extends JFrame {
    private JTextField nameField;
    private JLabel outputLabel;

    public GreetApp() {
        setTitle("Greet Application");
        setSize(350, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
```

*Textual explanation:* The class extends `JFrame` (a top-level Swing window). Field declarations create the `JTextField` and `JLabel` as **instance variables** so the listener can access them. `setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` ensures the JVM terminates on close.

### Step 3 — Instantiate and configure the JTextField

```java
        nameField = new JTextField(10);                 // 10 columns wide
        nameField.setToolTipText("Enter your name here");
        nameField.setHorizontalAlignment(JTextField.CENTER);
        add(nameField);
```

*Textual explanation:* `new JTextField(10)` reserves preferred space for **10 monospace characters**. `setToolTipText` adds a hover hint. `setHorizontalAlignment(CENTER)` visually centers input text. `add()` places the field into the frame's `FlowLayout`.

### Step 4 — Create the button and label

```java
        JButton greetBtn = new JButton("Greet");
        outputLabel = new JLabel("Type your name and press Enter.");
        add(greetBtn);
        add(outputLabel);
```

*Textual explanation:* The button is **local** (not a field) because we don't need to access it from the listener. The label is an **instance field** because we *will* mutate it.

### Step 5 — Register listeners (the Event Handling core)

```java
        // Handler logic extracted to a private method to share between sources
        ActionListener handler = new ActionListener() {
            @Override
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                String name = nameField.getText().trim();
                if (name.isEmpty()) {
                    outputLabel.setText("Name cannot be empty!");
                } else {
                    outputLabel.setText("Hello, " + name + "!");
                    nameField.setText("");     // clear field
                    nameField.requestFocus();  // refocus for next input
                }
            }
        };

        greetBtn.addActionListener(handler);   // Register on button
        nameField.addActionListener(handler);  // Register on text field (Enter key)
```

*Textual explanation:* This is the **key step**. A single `ActionListener` object (an *anonymous inner class*) is created and registered to **two event sources** — demonstrating **listener reusability**. The same `handler` object fires when:
- The user clicks the "Greet" button → `greetBtn` fires `ActionEvent`.
- The user presses **Enter** inside the text field → `nameField` fires `ActionEvent`.

Both trigger `actionPerformed(e)`. The parameter `e` is an `ActionEvent` whose `getSource()` method would tell us *which* source fired — useful in advanced programs.

### Step 6 — Make the frame visible

```java
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new GreetApp());
    }
}
```

*Textual explanation:* `setVisible(true)` paints the window. `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(...)` schedules the GUI creation on the **Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)** — the **thread-safe, mandatory** way to launch any Swing app (per KTU 2024 best-practices).

### 3.1.1 Expected Output (Analytical Result)

| User Action | Field State | Label Output |
|-------------|-------------|--------------|
| Types "Anu", clicks Greet | "" (cleared) | "Hello, Anu!" |
| Presses Enter with empty field | "" | "Name cannot be empty!" |
| Types "Rahul", presses Enter | "" | "Hello, Rahul!" |

## 3.2 Problem Scenario 2 — Using a Named Listener Class (WindowAdapter + KeyAdapter)

> **Specification:** Extend the previous app: close the window on the "X" button click (using `WindowAdapter`), and **clear the label** whenever the user presses any key inside the field (using `KeyAdapter` — overrides only `keyPressed`).

### Step 1 — Outer class

```java
public class GreetAppV2 extends JFrame {
    private JTextField nameField;
    private JLabel outputLabel;

    public GreetAppV2() {
        setTitle("Greet v2");
        setSize(350, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE); // manual handling
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        nameField = new JTextField(10);
        outputLabel = new JLabel("Type your name.");
        add(nameField);
        add(outputLabel);

        // ======== WindowListener via WindowAdapter ========
        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.out.println("Closing application...");
                dispose();
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        // ======== KeyListener via KeyAdapter ========
        nameField.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
                outputLabel.setText("You pressed: " + e.getKeyChar());
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new GreetAppV2());
    }
}
```

*Textual explanation:*
- `setDefaultCloseOperation(DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE)` disables auto-close so the `WindowListener` is the **only** exit path — giving us a chance to save state or ask "Are you sure?" in a real app.
- `WindowAdapter` is a class that **implements all 7 methods of `WindowListener` as empty bodies**. We override only `windowClosing`.
- `KeyAdapter` provides empty `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased`. We override only `keyPressed`.
- `e.getKeyChar()` returns the `char` representation of the key — e.g., pressing **A** returns `'a'`. For non-character keys (Shift, F1), it returns `KeyEvent.CHAR_UNDEFINED` (`\uFFFF`).

### 3.2.1 Comparison Matrix — When to Use What

| Approach | Code Verbosity | Best For | Drawback |
|----------|---------------|----------|----------|
| Anonymous `ActionListener` | Low | Single-source single-handler | Can't easily share across classes |
| Named inner-class listener | Medium | Shared handlers, multiple methods | More boilerplate |
| **Adapter class** | **Lowest for multi-method listeners** | **Use only 1-2 of many callbacks** | Slightly more indirection |
| **Lambda expression** (Java 8+) | **Lowest overall** | Single-method listeners (Action, Item, etc.) | Not allowed on multi-method interfaces like `KeyListener` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Note:** Lambdas (e.g., `btn.addActionListener(e -> label.setText("Hi"))`) are allowed since the syllabus mandates Java 8+ knowledge. However, for `KeyListener` / `WindowListener` (multi-method), you **must** use the **adapter class** or anonymous class — lambdas cannot implement multiple methods.

## 3.3 Problem Scenario 3 — Identifying the Event Source (Advanced)

> **Question Pattern:** *"One listener registered on two sources — how do you know which fired?"*

```java
ActionListener common = e -> {
    Object src = e.getSource();           // returns the component that fired
    if (src == nameField) {
        outputLabel.setText("Enter from field: " + nameField.getText());
    } else if (src == greetBtn) {
        outputLabel.setText("Click from button: " + nameField.getText());
    }
};
```

*Textual explanation:* `ActionEvent.getSource()` returns an `Object` — the *actual reference* of the component that generated the event. Comparing with `==` (reference equality) is the canonical KTU-recommended way, since references are unique.
