## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Five Mandatory Steps of Any JDBC Operation

Regardless of whether you are performing Create, Read, Update, or Delete, every JDBC program follows this canonical 5-step structure:

1. **Import the JDBC Package:** Add `import java.sql.*;` and any vendor-specific driver import.
2. **Register / Load the JDBC Driver:** Use `Class.forName("driver_class_name")` (modern JDBC auto-loads drivers via SPI).
3. **Establish a Connection:** Call `DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, password)` to open a session.
4. **Create and Execute a Statement:** Use `Statement` or `PreparedStatement` to fire SQL.
5. **Close the Connection:** Always release resources (best done via try-with-resources).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why these 5 steps?** They correspond to the OSI-like layered model of JDBC: **Application Layer** → **JDBC API Layer** → **JDBC Driver Manager Layer** → **Database Driver Layer** → **Database Engine**. Each step transitions you to a lower layer until the SQL finally reaches the database.

### 2.2 Core JDBC Classes and Interfaces — The KTU Cheat Sheet

| Class / Interface | Package | Purpose | Key Methods |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DriverManager` | `java.sql` | Manages the list of database drivers and provides connection factory | `getConnection(url, user, pwd)` |
| `Connection` | `java.sql` | Represents an active session with a specific database | `createStatement()`, `prepareStatement(sql)`, `close()`, `setAutoCommit()` |
| `Statement` | `java.sql` | Used to execute **static** SQL statements (no parameters) | `executeQuery(sql)`, `executeUpdate(sql)`, `execute(sql)` |
| `PreparedStatement` | `java.sql` | Precompiled SQL with **parameter placeholders (`?`)** | `setString()`, `setInt()`, `executeQuery()`, `executeUpdate()` |
| `ResultSet` | `java.sql` | Represents tabular data returned by a `SELECT` query | `next()`, `getString(col)`, `getInt(col)`, `close()` |
| `ResultSetMetaData` | `java.sql` | Provides information about `ResultSet` columns (count, names, types) | `getColumnCount()`, `getColumnName(i)` |
| `SQLException` | `java.sql` | Checked exception for all database access errors | `getMessage()`, `getErrorCode()`, `getSQLState()` |

### 2.3 The `Statement` vs `PreparedStatement` Decision Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> This is a **favourite KTU question**. Memorize this table — it appears in nearly every Model Question Paper.

| Feature | `Statement` | `PreparedStatement` |
|---|---|---|
| SQL Compilation | Compiled **every time** it is executed | Compiled **once**, cached, then re-used |
| SQL Injection Protection | **Vulnerable** (string concatenation) | **Safe** (uses `?` placeholders) |
| Performance for repeated queries | Slow | **Fast** (precompiled) |
| Parameter Binding | Manual via string concatenation (`"WHERE id=" + id`) | Built-in via `setXxx(index, value)` |
| Readability of Code | Poor for dynamic queries | **Excellent** |
| KTU Recommended Choice | Only for static DDL queries | **Default choice for all CRUD** |

### 2.4 Mapping CRUD to SQL

| Operation | CRUD Letter | SQL Verb | `executeXxx()` Method | Returns |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Create a new row | **C** | `INSERT` | `executeUpdate()` | `int` (rows affected) |
| Read existing rows | **R** | `SELECT` | `executeQuery()` | `ResultSet` |
| Update existing rows | **U** | `UPDATE` | `executeUpdate()` | `int` (rows affected) |
| Delete existing rows | **D** | `DELETE` | `executeUpdate()` | `int` (rows affected) |

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

JDBC CRUD operations are the foundation of **virtually every enterprise software system**: banking transactions (read balance, update balance), e-commerce order management (create order, read order history, update status, cancel/delete), student management systems (KTU's own ERP!), IoT data logging, and inventory management. In modern stacks, frameworks like **Hibernate** and **Spring Data JPA** are built *on top of* raw JDBC — so mastering JDBC gives you a clear understanding of what those frameworks automate.

