## 3. Step-by-Step Derivation & Analytical Matrix — Full Java Implementations

This section is the **meatiest** part. We will build, line by line, a complete `Student` management program that demonstrates **all four** CRUD operations. Assume a MySQL table `students(id INT, name VARCHAR, age INT, grade VARCHAR)`.

### 3.1 Setup — Database Schema and Utility Class

**SQL DDL (run once in MySQL Workbench / CLI):**
```sql
CREATE DATABASE ktu_oop_db;
USE ktu_oop_db;
CREATE TABLE students (
    id    INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name  VARCHAR(50)  NOT NULL,
    age   INT,
    grade VARCHAR(10)
);
```

**Assumed Connection Parameters (used throughout the code):**

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Host | `localhost` |
| Port | `3306` |
| Database | `ktu_oop_db` |
| Username | `root` |
| Password | `admin123` |
| Full URL | `jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db` |

### 3.2 CREATE Operation — `INSERT` a New Student

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDAO_Create {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db";
        String user = "root";
        String pass = "admin123";

        // Step 1: Try-with-resources auto-closes Connection and PreparedStatement
        try {
            // Step 2: Register driver (optional in modern JDBC 4.0+, but shown for clarity)
            Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

            // Step 3: Open a Connection
            Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);

            // Step 4: Build parameterized SQL — '?' are placeholders (NOT concatenated strings)
            String sql = "INSERT INTO students(name, age, grade) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";
            PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql);

            // Step 5: Bind user input to the placeholders (1-indexed!)
            pst.setString(1, "Aravind");   // 1st '?' = name
            pst.setInt(2, 21);             // 2nd '?' = age
            pst.setString(3, "A");         // 3rd '?' = grade

            // Step 6: Execute — INSERT uses executeUpdate() which returns rows affected
            int rowsInserted = pst.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println(rowsInserted + " row(s) inserted successfully.");

        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("MySQL JDBC Driver not found.");
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

**Line-by-Line Logical Analysis:**

1. `Class.forName(...)` → Forces the JVM to load the driver class, registering it with `DriverManager`.
2. `DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)` → Establishes a TCP session to the MySQL server on port 3306.
3. `con.prepareStatement(sql)` → Sends the SQL to the DB, the DB parses/compiles/optimizes it **once**, and returns a handle.
4. `pst.setString(1, "Aravind")` → The 1st `?` is bound to a String value. Type-safety is enforced by the driver.
5. `pst.executeUpdate()` → Executes an `INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE` and returns the **number of rows affected** as an `int`.
6. The `try-with-resources` block (not shown in the abbreviated version, but recommended) automatically calls `close()` on `con` and `pst` to release the TCP socket.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why use `?` placeholders?** If a user types `'; DROP TABLE students; --` as the name, `Statement` with string concatenation will execute the malicious drop. `PreparedStatement` treats the input **strictly as a value**, not as executable SQL — this is the foundation of **SQL injection defense**.

### 3.3 READ Operation — `SELECT` All Students

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDAO_Read {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db";
        String user = "root";
        String pass = "admin123";

        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)) {

            String sql = "SELECT id, name, age, grade FROM students";
            Statement st = con.createStatement();        // Static SQL → Statement is fine
            ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(sql);          // SELECT → executeQuery()

            // Iterate the cursor row by row
            while (rs.next()) {
                int    id    = rs.getInt("id");
                String name  = rs.getString("name");
                int    age   = rs.getInt("age");
                String grade = rs.getString("grade");

                System.out.println(id + " | " + name + " | " + age + " | " + grade);
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

**Logical Analysis of the Read Pattern:**

- `rs.next()` → Moves the cursor forward by one row. Initially the cursor is positioned **before the first row**, so the first call returns `true` if the table is non-empty.
- `rs.getXxx("columnName")` → Retrieves the value of the named column from the **current** row.
- The cursor pattern mimics an iterator — JDBC `ResultSet` is a streaming cursor, not an in-memory `List`. For very large tables, this is memory-efficient.

### 3.4 UPDATE Operation — `UPDATE` a Student's Grade

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDAO_Update {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db";
        String user = "root";
        String pass = "admin123";

        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)) {

            String sql = "UPDATE students SET grade = ? WHERE id = ?";
            PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql);

            pst.setString(1, "A+");   // New grade
            pst.setInt(2, 101);       // Target student id

            int rowsUpdated = pst.executeUpdate();
            if (rowsUpdated > 0) {
                System.out.println("Updated grade for student id 101.");
            } else {
                System.out.println("No student with id 101 found.");
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

**Logical Analysis:**

- `UPDATE` is parameterized: only the **target row** (filtered by `id = ?`) is modified.
- `executeUpdate()` returns the **count of rows affected**. A return value of `0` is meaningful — it indicates *no row matched the WHERE clause*, which is a critical validation signal in production systems.
- Without the `WHERE` clause, **every** row in the table would be updated — a classic "DBA horror story" you must always avoid in exams.

### 3.5 DELETE Operation — `DELETE` a Student

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDAO_Delete {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String url  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db";
        String user = "root";
        String pass = "admin123";

        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass)) {

            String sql = "DELETE FROM students WHERE id = ?";
            PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql);
            pst.setInt(1, 101);

            int rowsDeleted = pst.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println(rowsDeleted + " row(s) deleted.");

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

**Logical Analysis:**

- Same `executeUpdate()` mechanism as `INSERT` and `UPDATE` — all DML (Data Manipulation Language) operations use it.
- Again, omitting `WHERE` deletes the **entire table**. KTU examiners often test whether students understand this safety criticality.

### 3.6 Consolidated CRUD Master Program (DAO Pattern)

The following is a **clean, exam-ready, single-file** demonstration of all four operations, structured as a minimal DAO (Data Access Object):

```java
import java.sql.*;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class StudentDAO {
    private static final String URL  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktu_oop_db";
    private static final String USER = "root";
    private static final String PASS = "admin123";

    // ---------- CREATE ----------
    public static void createStudent(String name, int age, String grade) {
        String sql = "INSERT INTO students(name, age, grade) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS);
             PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {
            pst.setString(1, name);
            pst.setInt(2, age);
            pst.setString(3, grade);
            pst.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println("Student created.");
        } catch (SQLException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }

    // ---------- READ ----------
    public static void readStudents() {
        String sql = "SELECT id, name, age, grade FROM students";
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS);
             Statement st = con.createStatement();
             ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery(sql)) {
            while (rs.next()) {
                System.out.printf("%d  %-10s  %d  %s%n",
                    rs.getInt("id"), rs.getString("name"),
                    rs.getInt("age"), rs.getString("grade"));
            }
        } catch (SQLException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }

    // ---------- UPDATE ----------
    public static void updateStudent(int id, String newGrade) {
        String sql = "UPDATE students SET grade = ? WHERE id = ?";
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS);
             PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {
            pst.setString(1, newGrade);
            pst.setInt(2, id);
            int n = pst.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println(n > 0 ? "Updated." : "ID not found.");
        } catch (SQLException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }

    // ---------- DELETE ----------
    public static void deleteStudent(int id) {
        String sql = "DELETE FROM students WHERE id = ?";
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS);
             PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {
            pst.setInt(1, id);
            pst.executeUpdate();
            System.out.println("Deleted.");
        } catch (SQLException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }

    // ---------- DRIVER ----------
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        createStudent("Meera", 20, "B+");
        createStudent("Rahul", 22, "A");
        readStudents();
        updateStudent(1, "O");
        deleteStudent(2);
        readStudents();
    }
}
```

